title: ACT voluntary assisted dying scheme begins, allowing Canberrans to 'die with dignity' | ABC NEWS
description: Warning: The following video contains content that viewers may find distressing.  November 3 marks the beginning of the ACT's voluntary assisted dying scheme, making the territory the second-last Australian jurisdiction to legalise it.   For Canberran Gail Ford, it's about "choice" and "dignity".   Over the more than 20 years that Gail has lived with Parkinson's disease, it has steadily and determinedly stripped away her abilities, and her independence.  For those reasons and more, Gail wants the option of voluntary assisted dying. title: New concussion guidelines released for Australia and New Zealand | 7NEWS
description: World-leading national guidelines for concussion treatment have been officially released for Australia and New Zealand, covering all causes of concussion across the entire lifespan for both adults and children. The guidelines combat myths about prolonged rest, instead recommending 24-48 hours of rest followed by gradual return to light exercise, work and school activities. Professor Karen Barlow from the University of Queensland's Child Health Research Centre led the team developing these comprehensive guidelines to help healthcare professionals better manage the 30% of patients who experience persistent symptoms lasting over a month. Rue waited six hours after learning of fatalities before contacting the communications regulator and eight hours before informing Minister Anika Wells, while 600 calls were ultimately affected and three people died. The CEO apologised but refused to resign, stating another leadership change would not benefit Optus or its customers. title: US Ambassador interrupted by Cuba at UN | ABC NEWS
description: US Ambassador to the UN Mike Waltz was interrupted during a speech at the United Nations General Assembly by the Foreign Minister of Cuba, Bruno Rodriguez.   The General Assembly were due to vote on whether to condemn the United States' economic restrictions on Cuba.   "Mr Waltz, this is the United Nations General Assembly," Mr Rodriguez said. "It's not a Signal chat. Nor is it the House of Representatives."   He also said Mr Waltz was speaking in an "uncivilised, crude and gross way".  But Mr Waltz's speech was unable to convince many countries, with the UN General Assembly voting 165-7, with 12 abstentions to condemn the US economic embargo against Cuba. description: The Australian Federal Police have been working with Microsoft to develop AI tools to interpret Gen Z and Alpha slang to quickly identify children at risk of sadistic online exploitation.  New AFP Commissioner Krissy Barrett used her first speech at the National Press Club on Wednesday to announce the creation of Taskforce Pompilid, which will use the technology amongst a raft of measures to crack down on decentralised online crime networks.    The AFP is warning that young girls are being "hunted, stalked and drawn-in" by men using online networks to coerce them into carrying out serious acts of violence on themselves, their siblings or pets, in a "twisted type of gamification".  The Commissioner also offered practical steps to keep children out of harm's way.  "Let kids know they have the right to feel safe online and, if something feels uncomfortable, they can leave a chat at any time and tell a safe adult.   You can encourage safe conversations by talking regularly about online activities and apps, encouraging critical thinking, and reassuring kids that they won't be punished for coming forward if they think they have done something wrong.   Also, you can look out for warning signs that include self-harm, changes in eating or sleeping habits, sudden withdrawal from friends, families or activities, use of extreme behaviour, extreme language or symbols, and rejection of previously held morals.   Importantly, there are really practical and easy resources available, including how to make a report about child exploitation, at the AFP-led Australian Centre to Counter Child Exploitation website. That's www.acce.gov.au". she said.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: No rate cut until mid-2026, says NAB chief economist | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: Inflation has surged in the September quarter with consumer prices rising at an annual pace of 3.2 per cent, up from 2.1 per cent in the June quarter. The "trimmed mean" for the September quarter, which strips out the most volatile price moves up and down, came in at 1 per cent. The headline number was 1.3 per cent. On an annual basis, the trimmed mean lifted to the top of the RBA's target band at 3 per cent. It was much hotter than the RBA and market economists were expecting, squashing hopes of a rate cut next week. In fact, NAB chief economist Sally Auld told The Business NAB isn't expecting another rate cut until mid-2026. "No rate cuts for the rest of this year, likely no rate cuts in the first quarter of next year, but we do have one more rate cut in our profile but not until May of 2026," She said. "I think really the message from today's numbers is that it is going to require a little bit of patience on the part of mortgage holders just to give the Reserve Bank a good chance to get comfortable and a bit more confident in terms of some of the underlying drivers of inflation."  #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE Read more here: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-10-29/september-quarter-inflation-kills-interest-rate-cut/105946770  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Parenting program rewires teenage brains | 7NEWS
description: A University of Melbourne study using MRI scans has shown that a parenting program called 'Tuning Into Teens' can physically rewire adolescent brains. title: King Charles heckled over brother Prince Andrew | ABC NEWS
description: King Charles was heckled by a protester on Monday over his brother Prince Andrew's ties to the late sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. The king was greeting royal fans during a cathedral visit in Britain.  "How long have you known about Andrew and Epstein?," the man could be heard shouting outside Lichfield Cathedral in northwest England, close to Birmingham.  Although Prince Andrew, 65, said this month that he would give up using his title of Duke of York after years of scrutiny over his behaviour and connections to Epstein, questions about him ‚Äî and what the royals knew of events ‚Äî have intensified since.  The contents of a posthumous memoir by Virginia Giuffre, who accused the prince of sexually abusing her as a teenager, have triggered renewed backlash over the issue this month.  Andrew has always denied Giuffre's account. In 2022, he made an undisclosed payment to settle a lawsuit brought in the US by Giuffre, who died by suicide in April.  British police are looking into media reports that in 2011 Andrew had asked one of his police officers to dig up dirt on Giuffre.  The protester could also be heard saying: "Have you asked the police to cover up for Andrew? ... Should the MPs (members of parliament) be allowed to debate the royals in the House of Commons?"  The monarch ignored the protester and carried on engaging with other members of the public.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. description: A man and a woman are dead after an explosion at an underground mine in western New South Wales. title: Donald Trump says he 'would love' third term | ABC NEWS
description: US President Donald Trump ruled out running for the vice presidency in the 2028 election, an approach some of his supporters have floated to allow the Republican president to serve an additional term in office. The remarks were Trump's latest on the subject, which he has teased in public remarks and with "Trump 2028" hats he hands out at the White House. No one may be elected to the US presidency a third time, according to the 22nd Amendment of the US Constitution. Some have suggested that one way around this prohibition would be for Trump to stand as vice president, while another candidate stood for president and resigned, letting Trump again assume the presidency. Opponents have disputed whether this would be legal. Referring to Vice President JD Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Trump also said they were "great people" who could run for the office. description: Hurricane Melissa has been upgraded to a Category 5 system, the highest level on the Saffir-Simpson scale, with sustained winds reaching 265 kilometres an hour. title: Trump Again Refuses To Rule Out Third Presidential Run | 10 News
description: US President Donald Trump has once again refused to categorically rule out attempting to run for a third presidential term, further stoking rising fears he may try to subvert the US constitution.  The constitution's 22nd amendment prevents anyone from being elected to the office of president more than twice. However, this hasn't stopped rampant speculation that Trump will mount a move to either remain in office in 2028, or find a legal workaround to permit a third tilt at the presidency.  Speaking aboard Air Force One, Trump was asked point-blank if he would rule out a third run. "Am I ruling it out? You tell me," he responded. Trump did, however, address one popularly held theory that he could run as Vice President behind JD Vance, with Vance immediately stepping down after winning an election. Despite that too being constitutionally forbidden, Trump said he would not do it because "it's too cute." title: ACCC takes Microsoft to court over misleading subscriptions | 7NEWS
description: The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission is taking Microsoft to federal court, alleging the tech giant misled 2.7 million Australian subscribers about their Office 365 subscription options. The ACCC claims Microsoft forced users to choose between upgrading to more expensive plans with AI co-pilot features or cancelling entirely, without disclosing cheaper 'classic plans' that maintained existing features at lower prices. Since co-pilot was added, subscription prices increased by $40-50, with the regulator seeking penalties, refunds and injunctions for affected consumers. title: John Fetterman savagely breaks with Democrats over Government shutdown
description: Democratic Senator John Fetterman has broken ranks with the Democrats to vote with Republicans to avoid prolonging a government shutdown.  The US government shutdown has now reached one of the longest in US history as Democrats and Republicans battle over healthcare funding.  Fetterman and a few other lawmakers broke ranks with the party, voting with Republicans to reopen the government.  The Senate failed to advance a Republican bill to pay federal workers during the shutdown, falling short of 60 votes with a 54-46 vote.  Three Democrats, including John Fetterman, voted with the Republican Party.

title: Donald Trump‚Äôs deadline for Hamas to return hostage bodies looms
description: The deadline looms after US President Donald Trump gave Hamas 48 hours to return the deceased hostages. The president has denied on more than one occasion that the US will put boots on the ground in Gaza, but Trump says there are military forces in the region who could intervene. title: Foreign e-commerce platforms threatening Australian retail sector
